INSERT INTO Master_Copies VALUES ('rec-b4be5cec8fd1462c89467720fd45180d','Amasee','s, l,   d r(ri) m','Plagal do pentatone','Repeats, D.C., Community builder (dance)','q,h,ej',NULL,'ddm/rrd (2,f) ri/mdrl,/ddl,s, (*,3)','2/2','E407AEBB-ED83-405B-B0E0-3C6E925CD368.jpg',NULL,NULL,'Double line, partners facing each other.','“Swing your partner” and “take your partner” are repeated 3-5 times, Followed by group echo, “Amasee”.  The leader sings the solo part and Students sing group, “Amasee” section, clapping on strong beats.Begin with head couple, who sashays down the line or swings in place, Depending on what leader calls.  With each repetition of “take your partner”, A new couple sashays to the end of the line.  On “swing your partner”, the couple who has just come down the line swing as many times as leader indicates.  Similar to Virginia Reel, but students learn to actively listen to The directions, as they change often!','d-l,-s,','2.2.2.2','a.b.a.b.','a.b.a.b.','Call and Reponse','Play Party','Alabama','English','D-F',NULL,'Folk Music U.S.A., Vol. I.Smithsonian Folkways FE 4530 A6. Collected by Harold Courlander, 1950.  Informed by group of children, AL, 1950.  Taken from Holy Names University collection online, 11/26/11.','33 Amasee.wma','AMASEE.docx');
